  "text": "Measurements of radiation exchanges during this period highlighted net solar radiation as the major cause of radiative heating of water overlying the reef, with mean daily net shortwave radiation (K*) of 70.55 MJ·m −2 ·day −1 and mean daily net longwave radiation (L*) of −17.73 MJ·m . This was combined with light winds and high absolute humidity, ranging from 20 to 23 g/m 3 , which limited the potential for evaporative cooling of reef waters and low midday tides, so that water overlying the reef warmed quickly from around 28°C at 0900 AEST to~35°C by late afternoon. This period of extreme heating of waters overlying the reef highlights the importance of low tides around solar noon combining with light winds, high absolute humidity, and clear skies in causing rapid heating of reefs. These results are consistent with [CITATION_1] who also found that bleaching events were common during periods of low wind speeds, low Q e and Q h and therefore little evaporative cooling of reef surface waters. Collectively, these conditions result in the buildup of heat in the shallow waters overlying coral reefs with water temperatures far exceeding those of the surrounding",
